I thought the previous name was pretty good?
```suggestion
theorem typein_top {Î± Î²} {r : Î± â†’ Î± â†’ Prop} {s : Î² â†’ Î² â†’ Prop}
```

Yeah, but this clashes with the new `typein_top : (typein r).top = type r` (autogenerated by `simps`). I thought about maybe renaming that to `top_typein` but I think that's generally not the convention we follow for projection lemmas.
The new lemma should definitely be called `top_typein`. You can get `simps` to generate the `top` projection lemma names with `top_` as prefix, but I guess that's out of scope for this PR.

```suggestion
    ((PrincipalSeg.ofElement r a).codRestrict _ ?_ ha).ordinal_type_lt, type r, fun a â†¦ âŸ¨?_, ?_âŸ©âŸ©
  Â· rintro âŸ¨c, hcâŸ©
    exact trans hc ha
```
if you want
This doesn't work for whatever reason.
Uh okay

```suggestion
    exact (PrincipalSeg.ofElement ..).ordinal_type_lt
```
if you want
Personally don't think it's very useful to do this when there's only two arguments :P
I guess you'd prefer to use the new notation here?
The new notation is specifically for initial/principal segs between two `<` relations, but here we only have one of them!
Let's name the lemma this is deprecated in favour of.
This lemma would've been `Subsingleton.eq`, so the suggestion wouldn't have been very useful. I added `PrincipalSeg.eq` (matching `InitialSeg.eq`) and given that as the suggestion.
Although... given that you can't just apply `PrincipalSeg.eq` directly, maybe it is useful to have this lemma. I'll undeprecate it but keep the golfed version.
Let's have a SurjOn version of this too
I wonder if it might be more useful to have `x in range (typein r) iff x < type r` instead.
sure, why not both
Gotta go do other stuff, I'll add these results in a few hours :)
